s a key vision of successive Scottish administrations since devolution began. It is argued throughout this important book that the analysis of Scottish social policy must therefore be located in wider debates around social injustice as well as about how the devolution process affects the making, implementation and impact of social policy. Social justice and social policy in Scotland focuses on a diverse range of topics and issues, including income inequalities, work and welfare, criminal justice, housing, education, health and poverty, each reflecting the themes of social inequality and social justice. This book will be essential reading for academics, researchers, policy makers and practitioners as well as students of social policy and of society in Scotland and other devolved nations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aSocial justicezScotland. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Eddy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnott, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertram, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCroall, Hazel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDumbleton, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaw, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKee, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKendrick, John H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcPhail, Mo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMooney, Gerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMooney, Gerry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMore